observations.recommendation:
The Municipal Treasurer:

Enforce internal controls to immediately update all RPTARs maintained by the Office, taking into consideration the CY 2024 tax receivables;

Submit the duly certified list of showing the name of real property taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible for CY 2024 based on the updated RPTARs and submit to the Municipal Accountant for accrual thereof in the CY 2024 books of accounts;

Revise the template for the Abstract of Collections for real property and special education taxes taking into consideration the segregation of total discounts and penalties to separately account for such amounts in the CY 2024 books of accounts;  

Determine the accurate total discounts and penalties for real property and special education taxes for CY 2023 and submit to the Municipal Accountant for preparation of adjusting JEVs; and

Exclude in the distribution of shares to the Provincial Government of Cebu and the barangays advance payments received unless duly recognized as income by the Municipal Accountant.

The Municipal Accountant:

Prepare a JEV to adjust the misstatements in the Discount on Real Property – Basic and Discount on Special Education Tax accounts of ₱115,676.42 and ₱96,397.06, respectively; and

Prepare a JEV to adjust for the accurate total discounts and penalties for real property and special education taxes for CY 2023 to be determined by the Municipal Treasurer.

The Municipal Mayor ensures that the Municipal Treasurer cease the designation of Job Order and casual personnel as revenue collectors;



The Municipal Treasurer determines the total manpower needs of her Office, especially on the total additional revenue collectors; 

The Municipal Mayor initiates steps towards the revision of the approved plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the manpower needs of the Office of the Municipal Treasurer; and

The Human Resource Management Office (HRMO) initiates steps towards the hiring, reassignment and transfer of personnel to fill-in the vacant positions of the treasury office in accordance with civil service rules and in compliance with DBM LBC No. 137.

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials:

Initiate steps towards the revision of the plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality; 

Ensure that the HRMO initiate steps towards the filling-in of existing vacancies based on the revised plantilla, especially the vacant department head positions, with the end in view of maximizing the organizational structure; 

Hire casual personnel in accordance with the provisions of Section 9.g of the revised 2017 ORAOHRA; and

Hire Job Order workers only for the purpose of implementing local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160.

The Municipal Mayor, in coordination with the MPDC, Municipal Engineer and MBO to:

Review the unimplemented projects/programs and determine which among those are top priority and urgent and consider realigning the budget of other projects so that sufficient funds can be achieved instead of programming several projects/programs that remained not implemented due to insufficiency of the funds;


Post Invitation to Bid in PhilGEPS for the fabrication/installation of signage and landmarks project and if there are no bidders after two biddings, declare the failure of bidding and apply the alternative methods of procurement pursuant to the IRR of RA 9184;

Determine the specific locations of the streetlight and heritage site, negotiate with the lot owners for the road widening and resolve the conflict on the usufruct expeditiously to avoid further delay of the projects;


Review the design of the MRF projects and implement immediate corrections thereon; and

Refrain from indicating generic or lump-sum appropriation and include in the Annual Investment Plan, and eventually in the proposed budget itemized PPAs which are individually determined to be implementation ready.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the:
Municipal Accountant to locate or trace the documents of recorded infrastructure assets and provide the necessary depreciation in the books to reflect the correct book value of the infrastructure assets, hence to present fairly and reliably the FS; and include the necessary disclosure in the Notes to the FS pertaining to Road Network System;
General Services Officer (GSO) to prepare a Report of the Local Road Network which are covered by the Local Government Unit;
Head of the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network which should be submitted not later than January 31 of each year.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Determine the unclaimed retention money for its possible payment and coordinate with the Municipal Engineer for the issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance for these projects which will serve as their basis in the preparation of the Disbursement Voucher even without request for payment from the contractors/supplier;
Make a compilation of any record/ documentation and prepare the corresponding assessment/evaluation report as regards the long outstanding liabilities to support the possible reversion to unappropriated surplus in order not to overstate the liability accounts.  Likewise, support the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) with the Subsidiary Ledgers and all available records in case of reversion to the unappropriated surplus, so that if there may be claims in the future, the JEV would serve as the basis in requesting for a supplemental budget for the settlement of the payable;
Avoid setting up or recognizing payables at year-end without complete and valid documents supporting the claims. Thus, overstatement of liabilities at year-end will be avoided.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the CRAAF not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month to ensure proper monitoring of all accountable forms;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and submit the monthly Pre-Closing Trial Balance and SAAO not later that the 20th day after the end of the month, thus any discrepancy will be communicated to management for its immediate corrective action, thus facilitate the preparation of year-end FS, and the determination of the status and balances of the appropriations;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the monthly BRS in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011 to ensure the immediate reconciliation of the books and the depository bank in order to have accurate cash in bank balances at any given time.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
End-users or implementing units to prepare their respective PPMPs using the prescribed format, containing all PPAs under their units for the whole year, for consolidation into an APP (prescribed format) by the BAC Secretariat which will serve as a tool/guide of the agency to optimally utilize their resources, hence to meet the needs of the constituents or end-users at a favorable time.;
BAC Chairman and the Secretariat to submit the final APP, including amendments, revisions and supplemental, to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year;
BAC Chairman to cover all the necessary activities in the conduct of Pre-Procurement Conference in order to ensure readiness of the procurement at hand and ensure completeness of bidding documents;
BAC Chairman to make sure that the Technical Specifications for the procurement of infrastructure projects are duly prepared and approved and Technical Specifications and Schedule of Requirements for the procurement of goods are duly accomplished;
BAC Chairman to make sure that the Bid Data Sheet contains the minimum years of experience of key personnel and minimum major equipment requirements;
BAC Chairman to create a TWG, through a BAC resolution, and a copy of which should be attached in the Disbursement Voucher or submitted to the Audit Team;
BAC Secretariat to post the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period of 3 and 15 calendar days, respectively, in order to ensure procurement transparency;
BAC Secretariat to see to it that all documents submitted by the contractors, especially the Performance Security, are duly dated to ensure that said security was posted prior to the signing of the contract;
BAC Chairman to properly evaluate the eligibilities of prospective bidders in order to ensure that the SLCC requirement for the procurement of goods are met by the prospective suppliers in which the contract is awarded;
BAC, BAC Secretariat and TWG Members of the Municipality, at all times, be guided with the IRR of RA No.  in the procurement of goods and services, and infrastructure projects to avoid the sanction provided therein. Likewise, we encourage them to attend seminars related to the procurement processes to keep them abreast of the latest updates and issuances.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer:
Setup the correct RPT/SET receivables in the books based on the total amount due and collectible for the year from the certified list of taxpayers, to present accurate and reliable balances of receivable accounts in the financial statements;
Reconcile the balances of the RPT/SET Receivables with the updated List of Delinquent Tax Payers at year-end to ensure the correctness of the balances of the RPT and SET receivable accounts;
Maintain records such list or subsidiary ledgers that will support the balances of the receivable accounts; and
Make the necessary adjusting entry to correct the overstatement of P2,752,919.20 in the books of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory as required by COA Circular No. 2020-006.  Include all the physical assets of the Municipality in the inventory-taking located within and without the premises of the Municipality.  Prepare the RCPPE based on the prescribed format and the said report must be reconciled with the records of accounting unit to come up with accurate and reliable report;
The GSO maintain property cards of all the properties of the Municipality to facilitate recording and the retrieval of information on each property if needed.  Ensure that all PPEs are recorded and issuance thereof are documented to establish the accountable persons;
The HR to assess the current manpower in the GSO if it is adequate or not.  If warranted, initiate a recommendation to include in the plantilla more permanent positions in the said office so that it can fulfill its mandates efficiently and effectively.  Temporarily, assign casuals or contractual employees in the GSO to temporarily address the inadequacy of manpower, if necessary.

We recommended that:
The GSO or the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Agriculturist conduct quarterly inventory of the biological assets to validate the existence and physical conditions of these assets, and to properly record the growth, the offspring produce, and the death of these biological assets;
The Municipal Accountant record any gain due to growth or produced offspring and any death or disposal of these assets accordingly, based on the inventory submitted;
In case of death of animals, the Management require the concerned accountable person to report these deaths to concerned offices and to file a request for relief from property accountability to the COA Office and derecognition of the recorded value thereof in the books of the Municipality;
The Municipal Agriculturist and the GSO to maintain records in an organized manner of these biological assets these assets such as lists of recipients and contracts (under dispersal program), accountable persons, locations, and other documents pertaining to the biological assets of the Municipality;
The Management institute precautionary measures to safeguard these biological assets from preventable diseases, theft, and other factors that may harm them or stagnate their capacity to produce offspring.

We recommend that Management:
Update the alpha list data entry and the Monthly Alphalist of Payees (MAP) from time to time to ensure the correct amount of tax to be remitted and see to it that the amount withheld are posted in the right accounts;
Be reminded that withheld taxes for the month should be fully remitted within 10 days of the ensuing month to avoid any penalty pursuant to the BIR guidelines;
In cases where over-remittance was incurred by the agency, amend the BIR form filed and claim for tax credit, so that these may be applied in the next quarter.  No automatic offsetting must be made;
Ensure that BIR regulations and guidelines on the proper withholding of taxes and remittances thereof are strictly complied to avoid penalties and sanctions prescribed by laws above.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
For purposes of taxable income computation, ensure that the mandatory contributions deducted from the employees’ salaries and other compensations are correct and in accordance with the provisions of the Revenue Memorandum Circular No. 27-2011 and other BIR rules and regulations;
Revisit their computation of the employees’ taxable compensation income for the CY 2024, including the corresponding tax due, and make the necessary adjustments, if any, and amend previously issued BIR Form 1604c.  Inform the taxpayers about the additional taxes payable in order not to create confusions or misinformation and deduct discrepancies in their respective salaries;
Issue updated BIR form 2316 to the tax payers indicating the tax adjustment and remit unpaid balances through issuance of BIR 1700 before the 14th day of April 2025 at the Municipal designated BIR collecting officer;
For those separated from service, prepare a communication and issue an updated BIR Form 2316 for their information and require them to coordinate with the BIR for the settlement of their tax obligations; and
Be updated of the new issuances regarding tax compliance through active participation in BIR seminar and trainings, and regular visitation of the BIR website for news and updates.

We recommended that Management:
Designate a webpage administrator and instruct him/her to update and enhance the Transparency Seal page contents, patterned with the page's interface containing the information provided in Section 103 of GAA 2024, for ease of understanding, access and right to information of the public;
Instruct the concerned offices to submit to the webpage administrator the documents required to update the information contained in the Transparency Seal page of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Management:
Fill the vacancies which are provided with budget with qualified individuals by following the process of recruitment to reduce the list of casuals and job orders that are doing regular agency functions and to reduce also the charges in the maintenance and other operating expenses which could be used for other social services of the LGU. This will boost their morale and they may enjoy the benefits of a regular employee. Without regular hiring, continuous separation of employees due to retirement, dismissal, resignation and death, and new created positions, vacant positions will accumulate which affects the services of the Municipality;
Design policies or procedures that will maximize the services of both the permanent and non-permanent personnel involved in the administrative, clerical and utility works, such as assignment of multi-tasks to personnel (dual functions or serving two or more offices), centralizing personnel that provides janitorial services or centralizing procurement activities to GSO in line with appropriate rules and regulations;
Stop the assignment of one JO per one SB member in the Office of VM/SB, but instead, assess the need of the Office and assign only reasonable number of JOs that will augment the present permanent manpower of the office; and
Stop engaging the services of excessive and unnecessary casual, COS and JOs, and prudence must be exercised in the utilization of the limited funds of the Municipality.
Instruct the HRMO to:
Evaluate the accomplishments of each administrative, clerical, and utility workers to identify duplication or redundant responsibilities, and to immediately the recommend the termination of the contracts to avoid incurrence of additional unnecessary expenditures.  At the same time, asses the needs of administrative, clerical and utility of each office and designate a reasonable number of non-permanent personnel to complement the existing permanent personnel to deliver effective and efficient services.  Also, devise an accomplishment report that is quantifiable and specifically detailed and distinctive from the accomplishment of others to ensure that the services being paid are really rendered and earned by them;
Assess the existing organizational structure of the Municipality, taking into consideration the service requirements and financial capability thereof, to reduce the hiring of casual and COS/JO personnel.

We recommended to the Management the following:
The GSO and the BAC to plan and manage the supplies and equipment in stock of the Municipality by using the APP and PPMPs of the departments to ensure that these are available when they are needed in the operation of the Municipality;
All the Department Heads to:
stop the practice of purchasing the needs of their offices on their own, and instead submit RIS to the GSO to determine if these are available, and to prepare a PR if these are not available. This PR must be submitted to the GSO, for consolidation or for forwarding it to the BAC for processing;
require their employees to comply with the prescribed rules and regulations on the requisition, issuance, acceptance and inspection of the deliveries of supplies and equipment;
The Municipal Accountant, GSO and BAC to ensure that the procurements of goods are conducted in line with the prescribed rules and regulations, otherwise, these are deemed irregular transactions.

We recommended to the Management the following:
The BAC to validate the existence of all its Suppliers and ensure that the Municipality deals only with bona fide suppliers of known technical, legal and financial qualifications.  Awarding of contracts or POs to non-bonafide suppliers is deemed irregular and may be disallowed in audit;
The BAC to be more circumspect in the conduct of post-qualification of the Supplier to ensure that the technical, legal and financial qualification of these Suppliers are verified and ascertained, not just through perusal of documents submitted, but through other means like investigation, ocular inspection and others, especially those new Suppliers of the Municipality;
Stop the practice of awarding contracts thru middlemen and/or those who are not directly engaged in selling the products being procured, and if warranted, blacklist them from the roster of Suppliers; and
The BAC and the GSO to be more circumspect in the discharge of their functions and to abide by the provisions of RA 9184 to protect the interest of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the completion of the partially completed 2024 and prior years’ development projects;
Realign or reprogram the current year savings of 2024 and those of prior years for development PPAs, so that these will not remain idle, and their money value will translate into the betterment of the lives of the constituents of the Municipality;
Evaluate the unimplemented projects if these are still necessary, appropriate, or incidental to efficient and effective local governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare of the people, as well as if these are procurement-and-implementation-ready, otherwise, realign or reprogram the funds to other priority development PPAs that can be implemented immediately.  Ensure that those barangays downloaded with funds are technically and financially capable of implementing the projects.  If not, the Municipality must be the one to implement them so that development in the barangay becomes evident;
Ensure that the implementation of these projects under the 20% development funds are in line with the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, s. 2020.

We recommended that Management:
Establish standards in the derivation and assignment of contract periods of the project to prevent unnecessary longer contract periods that may cause the delay of the translation of the intended benefits to the stakeholders and the delivery of services of the Municipality.  Use the DPWH D.O. No. 44, s. 2012, as amended by DO No. 71, s. 2013, as benchmark in devising the standards;
In the absence of standards, adopt the applicable contract period prescribed by the Orders to have a standard determination of the contract period assigned to every project, and use shorter period if warranted;
Put the best interest of the Municipality in the programming of infrastructure projects and to ensure that these are expected to be completed within a reasonable and shorter period of time.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Compute the depreciation of Work/Zoo Animals account in accordance with IPSAS 17 and its PAG, and use the estimated useful life as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2003-007;
Record the depreciation expense of the Work/Zoo Animals in accordance with IPSAS 17 and following the PAJE as shown below:

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Create/reconstitute an Inventory Committee; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to recognize impairment loss pending disposal of the unserviceable properties to present fairly the PPE account balances in the financial statements.

Furthermore, we recommended and Management agreed, through the members of the Inventory Committee to:
Ensure that the physical count be conducted and participated by all the members of the said committee;
Revise the RPCPPE by indicating complete information on property number, unit of measure, quantity per property card, quantity per physical count, and shortage/overage, if any;
Provide details on the whereabouts, condition, and other relevant information under the “Remarks” column of the RPCPPE;
Maintain property cards per class of PPE; and
Ensure that the RPCPPE for each PPE account is duly signed.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Stop the practice of recording the procurement of rice as outright expenses and record the corresponding expense accounts only upon issuance and submission of the SSMI/RIS; and;
Classify the items properly based on the description of accounts in Annex B of the COA Circular No. 2015-009.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Agriculturist to conduct physical count of all the biological assets taking into consideration their biological transformation and maintain and update the records for breeding stocks. Also, submit a report thereon to the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer so that the respective records of these offices can be updated and reconciled purposely to present fairly the accounts in the financial statements;
Require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the books of accounts to reflect the correct fair value of the biological assets based on the results of reconciliation and maintain WOABSLC for each type of breeding stocks with sufficient details;
Demand payment from the accountable officer for the value of dead animals, effect necessary adjusting entries after and submit proofs of payment and adjusting entries, otherwise;
Require the accountable officer the immediate submission of the petition for relief from accountability together with its complete supporting documents.
During the exit conference, the Management informed to further their knowledge relative to monitoring and valuation of the biological assets which were reflected in the books of accounts.
9.24 The Audit Team will monitor the compliance of the Management as the breeding stocks account has not clearly valuated in the books of the municipality.

We have recommended that the Management: 

Optimally utilize the Municipality’s 20% Development Fund by ensuring that all PPAs under the said fund will be implemented timely in order to achieve the desired results intended for its beneficiaries;  

Prepare a comprehensive but realistic catch-up plan, after conducting proper monitoring and follow-up activities in order to expedite the project implementation of PPAs funded especially from prior years’ appropriation, which are still at the agency pipeline and to reduce backlogs;  

Consider the need for realignment of the PPAs from prior years’ appropriations, where necessary, after determination of a more relevant and responsive and procurement-and-implementation-ready projects that may be included under the 20% Development Fund of the Municipality in adherence with applicable laws, rules and regulations.

We	have
recommended that the Management:

Exhaust	all possible legal remedies	to enforce collection	of the outstanding Receivables;

For future loan agreements, ensure availability of complete
information and supporting documents needed	in enforcing collection	of the loans;

C. Instruct	the Accountant to effect	the necessary Adjusting Journal Entry amounting	to
₱2,513.00;
and

D. Refer to COA Circular No. 2016-05 dated December 19, 2016, for possible write- off of dormant accounts.

The Municipal Mayor:

Ensure implementation of program/projects/activities in which such Trust Fund bank accounts were set-up in order for these accounts to not be dormant or slow-moving, otherwise, initiate steps to return such funds to the source agencies and close the accounts;

Initiate steps to transfer the funds and close the dormant/idle bank accounts in the General Fund and Special Education Fund to the main accounts in LBP-Bantayan.

LDRRMO to identify the allotment for MOOE and CO on each PPA in the LDRRMFIP of 2023;

Municipal Budget Officer to record the appropriation for MOOE and CO in the RAAO to be able to determine the correct unspent/unobligated amount of each expense class as of year-end; and

Municipal Accountant to prepare adjustments in the books of accounts and/or deposit back to the general fund of any excess due to the inclusion of CO in the transfer to STF of unexpended balances of LDRRMF, if applicable, after the correct amount of unspent DRRM-MOOE is determined.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendations that the LCE: 

a) direct the Inventory Committee to (i) facilitate a one-time cleansing of PPE account balances through the implementation of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and (ii) prepare and submit RPCPPE in accordance with the MNGAS for LGUs; 

b) instruct the GSO to prepare and maintain property cards; 

c) require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the affected PPE accounts as discussed in paragraph 3.10.9; and 

d) give preferential attention in registering the eight parcels of land under the name of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Management:
Optimally utilize the Municipality’s 20% Development Fund by ensuring that all PPAs under the said fund will be implemented timely in order to achieve the desired results intended for its beneficiaries;
Prepare a comprehensive but realistic catch-up plan, after conducting proper monitoring and follow-up activities in order to expedite the project implementation of PPAs funded especially from prior years’ appropriation, which are still at the agency pipeline and to reduce backlogs;
Consider the need for realignment of the PPAs from prior years’ appropriations, where necessary, after determination of a more relevant and responsive and procurement-and-implementation-ready projects that may be included under the 20% Development Fund of the Municipality in adherence with applicable laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Management:
Establish policies and guidelines for the systematic disposal of unserviceable government properties pursuant to COA and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024 or the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties;
Form a disposal committee and instruct them to collate all the records of the unserviceable properties and to conduct disposal thereof in compliance with Section 79 of P.D. No. 1445, to lessen the bulk of unserviceable properties of the Municipality to save government resources and to generate additional income from sales that could be used to fund other projects/programs/activities of the Municipality;
For the missing properties, exert more effort to locate these properties and if not found, require the accountable person/s to prepare all the necessary documents and file the corresponding request for relief from property accountability thereof; and
Incorporate the inventory reports of the MO, MHO, SB, HRMO, MA, LCRO and MPDO, submit the complete RPCPPE report until April 30, 2024.  Ensure that the submitted RPCPPE for every year is complete in details, accurate and submitted promptly.

Nevertheless, for the noted unutilized balances, we recommended that the Management should:
Expedite the completion of the partially completed 2023 and prior years’ development projects;
Realign or reprogram the current savings of 2023 and those of prior years, so that these will not remain idle, and their money value will translate into the betterment of the lives of the people of Santa Fe;
Evaluate the unimplemented projects if these are still necessary, appropriate, or incidental to efficient and effective local governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare of the people, otherwise, realign or reprogram the funds to priority development PPAs; and
Ensure that the projects and the implementation of these projects under the 20% development funds are in line with the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, s. 2020.

We recommended that Management require:
The Contractors of the previous and newly constructed projects to submit the as-built plans for recording, safekeeping and future references;
All concerned personnel to comply with the documentary requirements prescribed by COA Circular 2023-004, particularly for the disbursement of progress and final payments of various projects of the Municipality to ensure the transparency and compliance with rules and regulations of the transactions;
The Municipal Accountant  and Municipal Treasurer to vigilantly ensure that the documentary requirements of the DVs are complete and proper before these are processed, approved, and paid to claimants; and
The responsible offices and personnel for the aforementioned documentary deficiencies to submit to COA Office, if available and possible,  or to explain in writing why these should not be suspended or disallowed in audit.

We recommended that Management should:
Instruct all the concerned personnel to ensure that all dates and other necessary information required in the various documentary requirements attached to the procurement of various goods must be filled out properly, completely and truthfully to ascertain compliance to applicable procedures, rules and regulations;
Inform the heads of the agencies and other concerned personnel that approval of POs must be made by the appropriate approving official of the Municipality in order that contracts entered into with the Suppliers are valid and effective;
Instruct the GSO to include the name of the canvassers in the RFQ to clearly establish their accountability as to the veracity of the canvass of prices or request for quotations made;
Inform the Suppliers and all the government employees of the Municipality that goods must be delivered directly to the GSO Office, to be duly accepted by them and inspected by the authorized inspector, before these are released to the end-users who will accept the goods through the RIS form; Ensure that the procedure of acquisition, requisition and issuance of goods are followed religiously;
Require the accounting unit and treasury unit to ensure that documentary requirements are all present and completely filled out before payments for these are processed and released, in compliance with Section 4 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445; and
Take measures to promote transparency and accountability in the management of public finances pursuant to Article 9, Chapter II of the United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC).

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation for the Municipal Mayor to instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and updated PPELCs to substantiate the reported balance in the year-end Financial Statements.

Similarly, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Reconcile the noted discrepancies between the GLs and PPELCs;
b. Analyze PPELCs of the PPE items with negative/abnormal balances and carrying values less than their residual value;
c. Ensure the completion of PPELCs, specifically regarding the Date of Acquisition, to facilitate proper depreciation monitoring of PPEs; and
d. Strictly monitor the PPELCs to prevent over-depreciation and occurrences of negative/abnormal PPE balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to verify the unremitted prior years’ contributions and/or loan amortizations for GSIS and PhilHealth and immediately remit or effect the necessary adjustment, if warranted.

Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

a. Provide a written explanation on the occurrence of over and/or under remittance of withheld contributions for PhilHealth, and employees’ GSIS and Pag-IBIG premiums and loan amortizations;
b. Analyze the SL accounts of the Due to Pag-IBIG (2-02-01-030) account, which exhibit abnormal debit balances of P172,502.04, after the posting of the remittances for the month of December, 2023. Draw the corresponding adjusting JEV, if warranted, and furnish the Audit Team for verification;
c. Verify the unremitted PhilHealth contributions and GSIS premiums and/or loan amortizations for CY 2023, and immediately remit or effect the necessary adjustment/s if warranted; and
Henceforth, strictly monitor the PhilHealth contributions, Pag-IBIG and GSIS premiums and/or loan amortizations to avoid accumulation of unremitted balances and over-remittance.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
a.Enforce internal controls to immediately update all RPTARs maintained by the Office, taking into consideration the CY 2024 tax receivables;
b.Submit the duly certified list of showing the name of real property taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible for CY 2024 based on the updated RPTARs and submit to the Municipal Accountant for accrual thereof in the CY 2024 books of accounts;
c.Revise the template for the Abstract of Collections for real property and special education taxes taking into consideration the segregation of total discounts and penalties to separately account for such amounts in the CY 2024 books of accounts;
d.Determine the accurate total discounts and penalties for real property and special education taxes for CY 2023 and submit to the Municipal Accountant for preparation of adjusting JEVs; and
e.Exclude in the distribution of shares to the Provincial Government of Cebu and the barangays advance payments received unless duly recognized as income by the Municipal Accountant.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
f.Prepare a JEV to adjust the misstatements in the Discount on Real Property – Basic and Discount on Special Education Tax accounts of ₱115,676.42 and ₱96,397.06, respectively; and
g.Prepare a JEV to adjust for the accurate total discounts and penalties for real property and special education taxes for CY 2023 to be determined by the Municipal Treasurer.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Ensure implementation of program/projects/activities in which such Trust Fund bank accounts were set-up in order for these accounts to not be dormant or slow-moving, otherwise, initiate steps to return such funds to the source agencies and close the accounts;
Initiate steps to transfer the funds and close the dormant/idle bank accounts in the General Fund and Special Education Fund to the main accounts in LBP-Bantayan.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure:
That the Municipal Treasurer cease the designation of Job Order and casual personnel as revenue collectors;
That the Municipal Treasurer determine the total manpower needs of her Office, especially on the total additional revenue collectors;
To Initiate steps towards the revision of the approved plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the manpower needs of the Office of the Municipal Treasurer; and
That the HRMO initiate steps towards the hiring, reassignment and transfer of personnel to fill-in the vacant positions of the treasury office in accordance with civil service rules and in compliance with DBM LBC No. 137.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials:
Initiate steps towards the revision of the plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality;
Ensure that the HRMO initiate steps towards the filling-in of existing vacancies based on the revised plantilla, especially the vacant department head positions, with the end in view of maximizing the organizational structure;
Hire casual personnel in accordance with the provisions of Section 9.g of the revised 2017 ORAOHRA; and
Hire Job Order workers only for the purpose of implementing local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor, in coordination with the MPDC, Municipal Engineer and MBO agreed to:
Review the unimplemented projects/programs and determine which among those are top priority and urgent and consider realigning the budget of other projects so that sufficient funds can be achieved instead of programming several projects/programs that remained not implemented due to insufficiency of the funds;
Post Invitation to Bid in PhilGEPS for the fabrication/installation of signage and landmarks project and if there are no bidders after two biddings, declare the failure of bidding and apply the alternative methods of procurement pursuant to the IRR of RA 9184;
Determine the specific locations of the streetlight and heritage site, negotiate with the lot owners for the road widening and resolve the conflict on the usufruct expeditiously to avoid further delay of the projects;
Review the design of the MRF projects and implement immediate corrections thereon; and
Refrain from indicating generic or lump-sum appropriation and include in the Annual Investment Plan, and eventually in the proposed budget itemized PPAs which are individually determined to be implementation ready.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the: 
 a. City Accountant and City Engineer to conduct reconciliation of records necessary to identify possible adjustments to records, aiding both records to reflect common description of road network components that is common to all reports; 
